List<String> planetDetail = [
  '''
Mercury is the smallest and closest planet to the Sun in our solar system. It has extreme temperature variations, with scorching highs of 430 degrees Celsius (800 degrees Fahrenheit) during the day and frigid lows of -180 degrees Celsius (-290 degrees Fahrenheit) at night. The planet's surface is heavily cratered, resembling the Moon, and is covered in grayish-brown dust. Its most significant surface feature is the Caloris Basin, one of the largest impact craters in the solar system. Mercury has a dense core made mostly of iron, generating a weak magnetic field about 1% as strong as Earth's. Its unique orbital pattern involves three rotations on its axis for every two orbits around the Sun, a phenomenon called tidal locking. This tidal locking is an important characteristic of Mercury's relationship with the Sun, resulting in a unique resonance in its rotation and revolution.''',
  '''Venus, the second planet from the Sun, is known as Earth's "sister planet" due to its similar size and rocky composition. However, Venus has a hostile environment with scorching temperatures that reach an average of 462 degrees Celsius (864 degrees Fahrenheit), making it the hottest planet in our solar system. Its thick atmosphere, primarily composed of carbon dioxide, creates a runaway greenhouse effect, further intensifying the heat. The planet's surface features vast plains, mountains, and numerous volcanoes, including shield volcanoes and extensive lava flows. Venus also exhibits unique topographical formations known as "coronae," resulting from tectonic activity. Venus has an extremely slow rotation, taking about 243 Earth days for one complete turn, while its orbit around the Sun spans approximately 225 Earth days.''',
  '''Earth, our home planet, is the third planet from the Sun and the only known celestial body to support life. With a diameter of about 12,742 kilometers (7,918 miles), it is the largest of the terrestrial planets. Earth has a diverse and dynamic environment, characterized by its vast oceans, continents, and atmosphere. It sustains a rich variety of ecosystems, from lush forests to expansive deserts, providing habitats for an incredible array of plant and animal species. The planet's atmosphere, predominantly composed of nitrogen and oxygen, shields us from harmful solar radiation and enables the existence of life as we know it. Earth's moderate climate and water resources have been crucial for the development and flourishing of human civilization. It completes a rotation on its axis every 24 hours, giving rise to day and night, while its orbital path around the Sun takes approximately 365.25 days, defining the length of a year. Earth is a precious and fragile planet, emphasizing the importance of environmental stewardship and sustainable practices to ensure its well-being and that of future generations.''',
  '''Mars, often referred to as the "Red Planet," is the fourth planet from the Sun in our solar system. With a diameter of approximately 6,792 kilometers (4,222 miles), it is smaller than Earth but larger than the Moon. Mars is known for its distinct reddish hue, caused by iron oxide (rust) covering much of its surface. The planet features a diverse landscape that includes vast plains, towering volcanoes, deep canyons, and polar ice caps. Mars is also home to the largest volcano in the solar system, Olympus Mons, and the longest canyon, Valles Marineris. Although its atmosphere is thin, composed mainly of carbon dioxide, it still plays a role in weather patterns and supports occasional dust storms that can engulf the entire planet. Scientists have been intrigued by the possibility of past or present microbial life on Mars, leading to numerous exploration missions and the search for signs of water, a key ingredient for life as we know it. In the future, Mars may serve as a potential destination for human exploration and colonization, raising questions about our ability to sustain life beyond Earth.''',
  '''Jupiter, the largest planet in our solar system, is a magnificent gas giant located fifth from the Sun. With a diameter of about 143,000 kilometers (88,846 miles), it is more than 11 times the size of Earth. Jupiter's distinct feature is its impressive system of colorful bands and swirling storms, the most famous of which is the Great Red Spot—a massive storm larger than Earth itself. The planet's atmosphere is mainly composed of hydrogen and helium, with traces of other compounds. Jupiter also hosts a multitude of moons, the four largest being called the Galilean moons—Io, Europa, Ganymede, and Callisto—each showcasing unique characteristics such as volcanic activity, icy surfaces, and potential subsurface oceans. Its immense gravitational pull acts as a protective force, deflecting asteroids and comets from entering the inner solar system. Jupiter's mesmerizing beauty and complex dynamics continue to captivate astronomers, providing valuable insights into the formation and evolution of planetary systems.''',
  '''Saturn, the sixth planet from the Sun, is a stunning gas giant renowned for its spectacular ring system. With a diameter of approximately 116,464 kilometers (72,367 miles), Saturn is the second-largest planet in our solar system. Its iconic rings are composed of ice particles, rocks, and dust, and extend over 280,000 kilometers (174,000 miles) from the planet's center. Saturn's atmosphere is primarily made up of hydrogen and helium, with traces of other compounds. The planet exhibits a banded appearance similar to Jupiter, but its bands are less prominent. Saturn also boasts a diverse collection of moons, with over 80 known satellites, including the impressive Titan, which has a thick atmosphere and hydrocarbon lakes on its surface. Saturn's captivating rings and moons make it a fascinating subject of study, contributing to our understanding of planetary formation and dynamics.''',
  '''Uranus, the seventh planet from the Sun, is a unique and mysterious ice giant in our solar system. With a diameter of approximately 51,118 kilometers (31,763 miles), it is the third-largest planet. What sets Uranus apart is its peculiar tilt—its axis is tilted almost 98 degrees, causing it to essentially roll on its side as it orbits the Sun. This axial tilt gives rise to extreme seasonal variations, with each pole experiencing 42 years of continuous sunlight followed by 42 years of darkness. Uranus has a predominantly hydrogen and helium atmosphere, with traces of methane that give it a pale blue-green color. The planet is enveloped by thick cloud layers and exhibits fast and violent winds. Uranus possesses a system of faint rings and numerous moons, the most famous being Miranda, known for its varied and intriguing surface features. Despite its distant and enigmatic nature, Uranus continues to fascinate scientists and spark curiosity about the mysteries of our cosmic neighborhood.''',
  '''Neptune, the eighth and farthest planet from the Sun, is a mesmerizing ice giant in our solar system. With a diameter of about 49,244 kilometers (30,775 miles), it is the fourth-largest planet. Neptune's distinct feature is its striking deep blue color, resulting from the presence of methane in its atmosphere. This gas giant is known for its tumultuous weather patterns, featuring high-speed winds and massive storms. The most notable storm on Neptune is the Great Dark Spot, similar to Jupiter's Great Red Spot, although it has been observed to come and go over time. Neptune also possesses a system of faint rings and a collection of intriguing moons, including Triton, a peculiar moon with a retrograde orbit and active geysers. As one of the outermost planets, Neptune's remote and dynamic nature continues to captivate scientists, providing insights into the complexity and diversity of our vast solar system.''',
];

